  "text": "The distinction between what might be termed speci c causal inference (there's something causal going on for the people in this experiment) and general causal inference (there's something causal going on for everybody in the target population) is particularly forceful in medical research, where|to judge from articles in leading journals over the past ten years|it is nevertheless routinely ignored. A typical recent example is a study by [CITATION_1] , in which 12 patients who presented at Mount Sinai Medical Center in Miami Beach with exercise-induced asthma during the last half of 1992 (and who in addition were selected on the basis of a number of intake criteria) were randomized into three groups of size four, one group receiving heparin, another cromolyn sodium, the third a placebo. A statistically signi cant di erence between the groups was found, in favor of heparin, and both the abstract (\\Inhaled heparin prevents exercise-induced asthma without in uencing histamine-induced bronchoconstriction\") and the discussion section of the paper read as if there is no longer any uncertainty about how everybody with this ailment should be treated.",
